><gtr:title>WHAT ARE THE CONSTRAINTS TO EMPLOYMENT INTENSIVE GROWTH IN INDIA? A study of the impact of economic reforms on labor intensive sectors</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>RES-072-27-0047</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>The formal manufacturing sector in India, despite its respectable growth following the reform process initiated in the 1980s and 1990s has not been able to perform its role of pulling workers away from agriculture and informal sector activities into the modern sector employment with higher productivity and wages. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>A look at India?s manufacturing performance over the two decades suggests that it has been a period of growth without employment creation- known as the phenomenon of ?jobless growth?.&amp;nbsp; After two decades of economic reforms beginning in 1991, the lack of competitiveness still constitutes an important barrier to the growth of the labour-intensive manufacturing sector in India. The reasons for this are not clear as an important objective of economic reforms was to encourage the growth of the labour-intensive manufacturing sector, given that India?s comparative advantage lay in labour intensive activities. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The aim of this project is to study the impact of industrial and trade policy reforms on the economic performance of labour intensive manufacturing in India and what the binding constraints to this sector?s growth may be. The methodology involves panel data econometric methods using detailed secondary data on Indian manufacturing available at the 3 digit ISIC level. &lt;br />&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2011-09-23</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2011-06-24</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>4770</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>A puzzling feature of India's post-reform economic development has been the sustained decline in labour-intensity in the organized manufacturing sector, especially in the labour-intensive industries. We find that this has occurred due to an increase in the real wage to rental price of capital ratio. This in turn has been mostly due to a fall in the relative price of capital goods, driven by trade reforms in capital goods, and falling import tariffs on capital goods over time. Therefore, while the fall in the relative price of capital may have led to an increase in the rate of private fixed investment in machines, and consequently, economic growth, one inadvertent consequence of the trade reforms was the disincentive to firms to hire labour, and to quicken the adoption of machines in their workplaces.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>The findings can be taken forward by the Indian government, especially the Ministry of Industry, in shaping policy towards jobs in India.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>55706B7E-1D18-49EB-AEE8-010F77B6FCF5</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>56d4690d781847.13952807</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Manufacturing, including Industrial Biotechology</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>41A8B482-B5DC-45B6-A46C-E9337E256405</gtr:id><gtr:title>Labour, Employment and Economic Growth in India</gtr:title><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/01b8da17f53f1c9518006161451a1eb7"><gtr:id>01b8da17f53f1c9518006161451a1eb7</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Das D</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2015-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>56d46be34ac060.98822021</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>AF154772-377F-497B-8B42-D681AFD5DB68</gtr:id><gtr:title>Where Have All The Workers Gone? The Puzzle of Declining Labour Intensity in Organized Indian Manufacturing</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Economic and Political Weekly</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/593043c01c1cdcd1ba506c055252e5ab"><gtr:id>593043c01c1cdcd1ba506c055252e5ab</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Sen, K</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2015-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>56d46b5d31e074.48625120</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication></gtr:publications><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RES">RES-072-27-0047</gtr:identifier><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">RES-072-27-0047</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories/><gtr:researchActivities/><gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>5D762B83-597E-4E91-B2F7-04CBB955175C</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Pol. sci. &amp; internat. studies</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject></gtr:researchSubjects><gtr